1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:19,000
 Gdje prijatelj te gdje načeka, gdje postoji ona tvoja njeka, snovi na putu i miri zamina, tu je tu srcu domovina, radio_mrežnica_.

2
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:24,000
 Dobrodošli u novo izdanje podcasta Mrežnica.

3
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:29,500
 I dok se u Hrvatskoj skupljaju i analiziraju još uvijek rezultati predsjedničkih izbora,

4
00:00:29,500 --> 00:00:33,500
 prava zvijezda godine na svjetskoj razini uskoro stupa na scenu.

5
00:00:33,500 --> 00:00:39,500
 Pogađate, on je Donald Trump i kroz nekoliko dana zasjest će u bijelu kuću.

6
00:00:39,500 --> 00:00:43,500
 Što će Trumpov dolazak značiti za Sjedinjene američke države?

7
00:00:43,500 --> 00:00:46,500
 Što za Evropu, što za ostatak svijeta?

8
00:00:46,500 --> 00:00:51,500
 Hoće li biti nastavljeni ratovi ili će doći možda do ekonomskog boljetka?

9
00:00:51,500 --> 00:00:54,500
 O svemu tome razgovaramo s našim današnjim gostom.

10
00:00:54,500 --> 00:00:56,500
 On je Larry C. Johnson.

11
00:00:56,500 --> 00:01:03,500
 Američki bloger, politički komentator i bivši analitičar u Središnjoj obavještajnoj agenciji CI.

12
00:01:03,500 --> 00:01:11,500
 Johnson je u CI radio četiri godine, a zatim je prešao u Ured za borbu protiv terorizma američkog State Departmenta.

13
00:01:11,500 --> 00:01:19,500
 Prošle godine govorio je i u Jedinjenim narodima, odnosno u Vijeću sigurnosti, oko okolnosti sabotaže sjevernog toka.

14
00:01:19,500 --> 00:01:24,500
 Neki će reći da ga ne vole niti lijevi, niti desni, što bi mogao biti dobar znak.

15
00:01:24,500 --> 00:01:31,500
 Johnson je čest gost stranih podkasta, a danas je i gost podkasta Mrežnica.

16
00:01:31,500 --> 00:01:35,500
 So, dear Mr. Johnson, I would like to welcome you, and thank you for joining us.

17
00:01:35,500 --> 00:01:38,500
 You're most welcome. Thank you for inviting me.

18
00:01:38,500 --> 00:01:39,500
 Great.

19
00:01:39,500 --> 00:01:43,500
 The world awaits the appointment of Donald Trump as the U.S. president.

20
00:01:43,500 --> 00:01:48,500
 So many questions remain open, from the war in Ukraine to the Middle East,

21
00:01:48,500 --> 00:01:52,500
 the situation in Europe and the U.S. itself.

22
00:01:52,500 --> 00:01:56,500
 What do you think Mr. Trump's first move will be?

23
00:01:56,500 --> 00:02:02,500
 Well, we've already seen the first move in terms of the ceasefire declared announced today

24
00:02:02,500 --> 00:02:05,500
 between Israel and Hamas.

25
00:02:05,500 --> 00:02:11,500
 This would not have happened without Donald Trump's intervention.

26
00:02:11,500 --> 00:02:18,500
 And again, it shows sort of the contradictory portrait of Donald Trump.

27
00:02:18,500 --> 00:02:24,500
 On the one hand, he's seen as reflexively pro-Israeli.

28
00:02:24,500 --> 00:02:30,500
 That he would be absolutely 100% on the side of the Zionists.

29
00:02:30,500 --> 00:02:32,500
 He'd be Netanyahu in his crowd.

30
00:02:32,500 --> 00:02:40,500
 Part of that was events because of his money he received from the widow of Sheldon Adelson,

31
00:02:40,500 --> 00:02:42,500
 a wealthy billionaire.

32
00:02:42,500 --> 00:02:47,500
 That's contrary, you know, I'm repeating myself.

33
00:02:47,500 --> 00:02:53,500
 A billionaire in Las Vegas, Jewish, who reportedly gave up to $100 million.

34
00:02:53,500 --> 00:02:58,500
 may have only been 50, but regardless, as soon as that came with the product,

35
00:02:58,500 --> 00:03:01,500
 you know, that money came with a obligation.

36
00:03:01,500 --> 00:03:07,500
 Of appointing, naming Marco Rubio to be Secretary of State against Rubio,

37
00:03:07,500 --> 00:03:13,500
 seen as one of these, I'll call him Christian Zionists, avidly supporting Israel.

38
00:03:13,500 --> 00:03:17,500
 Naming Steve Witkoff as a special envoy for the Middle East.

39
00:03:17,500 --> 00:03:23,500
 So he had this picture that he's going to be entirely on the side of Israel.

40
00:03:23,500 --> 00:03:31,500
 But then last week he released, he posted on Truth Social, a clip of Professor Jeffrey Sachs

41
00:03:31,500 --> 00:03:39,500
 speaking to the Cambridge Union, in which he referred to Bibi Netanyahu as a deep, dark,

42
00:03:39,500 --> 00:03:45,500
 and then referred to his mother and parentage in a very vulgar term.

43
00:03:45,500 --> 00:03:47,500
 accurate but vulgar.

44
00:03:47,500 --> 00:03:53,500
 Well, that was, you know, clearly an affront to someone like Netanyahu.

45
00:03:53,500 --> 00:03:55,500
 And it was Trump sending a message.

46
00:03:55,500 --> 00:03:59,500
 Then we get to reporting out of the Israeli media

47
00:03:59,500 --> 00:04:03,500
 that the special envoy for the Middle East for Trump,

48
00:04:03,500 --> 00:04:08,500
 Stephen Witkoff, who was assumed, because he is an Orthodox Jew,

49
00:04:08,500 --> 00:04:12,500
 it was naturally assumed he'd be entirely on the side of Netanyahu.

50
00:04:12,500 --> 00:04:17,500
 Yet he called up Netanyahu, he got a hold of his staff and said,

51
00:04:17,500 --> 00:04:20,500
 "I'm coming, I want to meet him Friday night."

52
00:04:20,500 --> 00:04:26,500
 And Netanyahu's staff said, "Oh no, it's Shabbat, you know, it's Sabbath, we can't do it."

53
00:04:26,500 --> 00:04:30,500
 And Sri Witkoff basically used some equally salty language

54
00:04:30,500 --> 00:04:35,500
 and said he didn't give a damn and that Netanyahu better meet with him, and he did.

55
00:04:35,500 --> 00:04:42,500
 And apparently it was not a pleasant system of session of pleasantries.

56
00:04:42,500 --> 00:04:45,500
 Witkoff made it very clear.

57
00:04:45,500 --> 00:04:51,500
 You better have a ceasefire in place before Donald Trump is inaugurated or else.

58
00:04:51,500 --> 00:04:57,500
 So, you know, that's why now they've announced a ceasefire.

59
00:04:57,500 --> 00:05:04,500
 And, you know, Hamas is going to release up 30 hostages.

60
00:05:04,500 --> 00:05:08,500
 And Israel is going to probably release around 2,000 prisoners.

61
00:05:08,500 --> 00:05:16,500
 That means Israel is still holding over 8,000 Palestinians as hostages.

62
00:05:16,500 --> 00:05:19,500
 There's no other way to view it.

63
00:05:19,500 --> 00:05:22,500
 But, you know, so Trump's already having an impact.

64
00:05:22,500 --> 00:05:26,500
 And as he just, he just put out on true social a little bit, go see,

65
00:05:26,500 --> 00:05:29,500
 and I'm not even in the White House yet.

66
00:05:29,500 --> 00:05:35,500
 Trump has said many times that America is his top priority.

67
00:05:35,500 --> 00:05:41,500
 It seems as if he is not interested in anything else, but is that true?

68
00:05:41,500 --> 00:05:43,500
 I think so.

69
00:05:43,500 --> 00:05:46,500
 Let's put it this way.

70
00:05:46,500 --> 00:05:48,500
 That's what he ran on.

71
00:05:48,500 --> 00:05:50,500
 That's what he said.

72
00:05:50,500 --> 00:05:58,500
 If he does not live up to that, then his presidency will be an abject failure.

73
00:05:58,500 --> 00:06:07,500
 If he follows through on that promise, putting America first and the interests of the people of America first,

74
00:06:07,500 --> 00:06:15,500
 I think actually he will become a historic president in a very good sense.

75
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:17,500
 But with Trump, you never know.

76
00:06:17,500 --> 00:06:21,500
 You know, he is a volatile personality.

77
00:06:21,500 --> 00:06:37,500
 He is clearly, you know, someone of incredible mental toughness because to have endured the unrelenting legal attacks that he put up with over the last four years is really remarkable.

78
00:06:37,500 --> 00:06:43,500
 I don't know too many people who would have been able to have withstood that and dealt with all the uncertainty.

79
00:06:43,500 --> 00:06:50,500
 You know, anyone that's had a lawsuit filed against them, you always get a pit, a rock in the pit of your stomach.

80
00:06:50,500 --> 00:06:54,500
 And there's fear and you can never predict which way it's going to go.

81
00:06:54,500 --> 00:06:56,500
 You don't have control of the situation.

82
00:06:56,500 --> 00:07:00,500
 And yet Trump, in spite of all of that, prevailed.

83
00:07:00,500 --> 00:07:08,500
 So I think if he continues to put America first and wars last, he'll be successful.

84
00:07:08,500 --> 00:07:12,500
 If he doesn't, then he will have dug his own grave.

85
00:07:12,500 --> 00:07:13,500
 Yeah.

86
00:07:13,500 --> 00:07:18,500
 So many expected the war in Ukraine to end once Trump takes office.

87
00:07:18,500 --> 00:07:20,500
 Is that possible?

88
00:07:20,500 --> 00:07:22,500
 It's possible.

89
00:07:22,500 --> 00:07:24,500
 Well, it's going to end.

90
00:07:24,500 --> 00:07:29,500
 Whether the United States has a say in that or not remains to be seen.

91
00:07:29,500 --> 00:07:38,500
 Trump can end it right away if on day one he informs Volodymyr Zelensky that I'm cutting off all funding to you.

92
00:07:38,500 --> 00:07:40,500
 There's no more aid coming.

93
00:07:40,500 --> 00:07:44,500
 And I'm recalling U.S. military and intelligence personnel.

94
00:07:44,500 --> 00:07:46,500
 We're done supporting you.

95
00:07:46,500 --> 00:07:49,500
 If Trump did that, yeah, the war would end immediately.

96
00:07:49,500 --> 00:07:52,500
 It would not be able to continue.

97
00:07:52,500 --> 00:08:01,500
 I doubt he'll do that, which means that Russia will continue to press forward with military advantage.

98
00:08:01,500 --> 00:08:03,500
 And the United States has no leverage over Russia.

99
00:08:03,500 --> 00:08:06,500
 You know, they say, well, we'll lift sanctions.

100
00:08:06,500 --> 00:08:08,500
 Russia goes, we don't care.

101
00:08:08,500 --> 00:08:13,500
 You know, we've lived more than two years now with sanctions.

102
00:08:13,500 --> 00:08:16,500
 And we'll continue living with them.

103
00:08:16,500 --> 00:08:25,500
 What we want, you know, what Russia wants, is these Ukrainians no longer to be equipped with weapons that can attack Russian people.

104
00:08:25,500 --> 00:08:34,500
 That the neo-Nazis that make up a significant political force in Ukraine be banned and eliminated from public office.

105
00:08:34,500 --> 00:08:35,500
 They not be allowed.

106
00:08:35,500 --> 00:08:46,500
 And that NATO stop providing weapons and conducting the military exercises in Ukraine, which also means pull back from our borders.

107
00:08:46,500 --> 00:08:48,500
 That's what Russia wants.

108
00:08:48,500 --> 00:08:54,500
 Whether NATO is willing to give that right now, I don't think so.

109
00:08:54,500 --> 00:09:05,500
 But Russia is going to, I think, ultimately compel NATO to accept that kind of deal by inflicting a severe military defeat on Ukraine.

110
00:09:05,500 --> 00:09:06,500
 You mentioned Mr. Zelensky.

111
00:09:06,500 --> 00:09:11,500
 What do you think will happen to Mr. Zelensky in the end?

112
00:09:11,500 --> 00:09:23,500
 He will either be killed in a coup launched by the military or he will flee to a safe haven overseas.

113
00:09:23,500 --> 00:09:28,500
 Now, this is one area there Donald Trump does have leverage.

114
00:09:28,500 --> 00:09:36,500
 The Trump's negotiator can sit in front of Vladimir Zelensky, hold up a passport and go, see this document?

115
00:09:36,500 --> 00:09:42,500
 If you want to get into the United States, this is what you're going to do.

116
00:09:42,500 --> 00:09:50,500
 If you refuse to negotiate, if you refuse to follow our guidance, you will not be welcome in the United States.

117
00:09:50,500 --> 00:09:56,500
 I think that would have a lot of leverage over Zelensky.

118
00:09:56,500 --> 00:10:05,500
 I don't see him, he's not the kind of person that's going to risk his survival by being stubborn.

119
00:10:06,500 --> 00:10:12,500
 After three years of conflict, how could we describe the war in Ukraine today?

120
00:10:12,500 --> 00:10:15,500
 Whose success is it and whose failure?

121
00:10:15,500 --> 00:10:20,500
 One thing is certain the victims are the Ukrainian people whose country has been devastated.

122
00:10:20,500 --> 00:10:21,500
 Right.

123
00:10:21,500 --> 00:10:23,500
 What are the biggest losers of this war?

124
00:10:23,500 --> 00:10:28,500
 Yeah, no, it's Ukraine and the Ukrainian men.

125
00:10:28,500 --> 00:10:36,500
 The casualties are estimated for, on the Ukrainian side, well in excess of one million.

126
00:10:36,500 --> 00:10:44,500
 The Russians have, by contrast, have suffered about 100,000 killed, probably 200,000 to 300,000 wounded.

127
00:10:44,500 --> 00:10:59,500
 That's a significant number, but it's not, it's not a devastating number where what Ukraine is facing is, as much as 60% of its military force has been put out of action.

128
00:10:59,500 --> 00:11:03,500
 And they don't have a reserve to go to.

129
00:11:03,500 --> 00:11:08,500
 So this is, this war is moving entirely in the favor of Russia.

130
00:11:08,500 --> 00:11:11,500
 Russia has the weapons, Ukraine doesn't.

131
00:11:11,500 --> 00:11:15,500
 Russia has trained manpower, Ukraine doesn't.

132
00:11:15,500 --> 00:11:19,500
 And Russia hasn't even mobilized on a war footing.

133
00:11:19,500 --> 00:11:26,500
 Everything right now is being done under the auspices of what they call the Special Military Operation.

134
00:11:26,500 --> 00:11:31,500
 The political events in the world have been quite hectic lately.

135
00:11:31,500 --> 00:11:34,500
 Europe is shaking, governments are falling.

136
00:11:34,500 --> 00:11:38,500
 Has Trump already shaken Europe with his friend Elon Musk?

137
00:11:38,500 --> 00:11:42,500
 Yes, to an extent.

138
00:11:42,500 --> 00:11:45,500
 Of course, a lot of it's self-inflicted in the part of Europe.

139
00:11:45,500 --> 00:11:47,500
 Let me take Germany as an example.

140
00:11:47,500 --> 00:11:55,500
 A German Chancellor Schultz stood by and said nothing, did nothing, as the United States destroyed the Nord Stream pipeline,

141
00:11:55,500 --> 00:12:01,500
 which really plunged Germany into economic chaos and decline.

142
00:12:01,500 --> 00:12:05,500
 You know, he didn't even speak up to defend himself.

143
00:12:05,500 --> 00:12:12,500
 It's like, it's like a man allowing some other man to, you know, rape his wife or girlfriend.

144
00:12:12,500 --> 00:12:17,500
 I mean, sorry to use such a crude analogy, but that, that's exactly what it was.

145
00:12:17,500 --> 00:12:20,500
 It was that brutal to Germany, to the German people.

146
00:12:20,500 --> 00:12:24,500
 You know, their industry is in collapse right now.

147
00:12:24,500 --> 00:12:38,500
 And despite constant claims from the likes of Joe Biden and the new Secretary General of NATO, Ruta, that NATO is as strong as ever.

148
00:12:38,500 --> 00:12:40,500
 We're totally united.

149
00:12:40,500 --> 00:12:42,500
 Oh, wait a second.

150
00:12:42,500 --> 00:12:44,500
 Dude, go talk to Hungary.

151
00:12:44,500 --> 00:12:48,500
 Go talk to the new Prime Minister of Croatia.

152
00:12:48,500 --> 00:12:50,500
 Go talk to Robert Fico in Slovakia.

153
00:12:50,500 --> 00:12:51,500
 The new president.

154
00:12:51,500 --> 00:12:52,500
 The new president.

155
00:12:52,500 --> 00:12:53,500
 The new president, yes.

156
00:12:53,500 --> 00:12:55,500
 Yeah, the new president in Croatia.

157
00:12:55,500 --> 00:12:56,500
 Yes.

158
00:12:56,500 --> 00:13:01,500
 So, and then in Romania, the Romanian people have taken to the streets.

159
00:13:01,500 --> 00:13:17,500
 They're going to elect somebody who will reject the NATO position, which is, you know, really critical from a NATO standpoint, because at this point, Romania is supposed to host the largest base in NATO inside Romania.

160
00:13:17,500 --> 00:13:22,500
 The government of Austria also has decidedly shifted.

161
00:13:22,500 --> 00:13:24,500
 I don't, they say it's shifted to the right.

162
00:13:24,500 --> 00:13:43,500
 But, you know, now we're in this, you know, I'm old enough to remember that back in the day in 1980, you know, 40 years ago, 45 years ago, when we talked about right wing, we're talking about people who favored war, who favored aggressive foreign policy and military action.

163
00:13:43,500 --> 00:13:52,500
 Now, here we are 45 years later, these actions are, you know, are anti-war.

164
00:13:52,500 --> 00:13:58,500
 These so-called right wingers are against war and against increasing foreign entanglements.

165
00:13:58,500 --> 00:14:01,500
 So, you know, the world sort of flipped upside down.

166
00:14:01,500 --> 00:14:17,500
 But the point of the fact is, there is not a single government in Europe, possibly with the exception of Maloney in Italy, where the current leader enjoys widespread support, just the opposite.

167
00:14:17,500 --> 00:14:22,500
 The current leaders enjoy very, very small and declining support.

168
00:14:22,500 --> 00:14:28,500
 And at the same time, there is no single opposition party that has taken a majority view.

169
00:14:28,500 --> 00:14:36,500
 Instead, you run, it's like I think with AfD in Germany, as an example, they can, they garner 30% of the vote.

170
00:14:36,500 --> 00:14:41,500
 Well, that's a plurality, but that's not a majority.

171
00:14:41,500 --> 00:14:43,500
 They don't have what Donald Trump has.

172
00:14:43,500 --> 00:14:45,500
 Donald Trump won a majority.

173
00:14:45,500 --> 00:14:48,500
 Majority of votes and a majority in the Electoral College.

174
00:14:48,500 --> 00:14:51,500
 You don't have anybody like that in Europe right now.

175
00:14:51,500 --> 00:14:55,500
 And that makes Europe even shakier, more susceptible to chaos.

176
00:14:55,500 --> 00:15:02,500
 Let's talk about NATO's push, or increased military spending.

177
00:15:02,500 --> 00:15:07,500
 Trump's proposal to increase defense spending is unattainable for many.

178
00:15:07,500 --> 00:15:10,500
 Europe has not been at war for decades.

179
00:15:10,500 --> 00:15:14,500
 As an expert, how would you assess Europe's military state?

180
00:15:14,500 --> 00:15:18,500
 Is Europe weak or strong?

181
00:15:18,500 --> 00:15:24,500
 Have you ever known a recent college graduate, someone who's come out of university?

182
00:15:24,500 --> 00:15:28,500
 And they've got a credit card.

183
00:15:28,500 --> 00:15:32,500
 And they now owe $50,000 on that credit card.

184
00:15:32,500 --> 00:15:37,500
 And they had a job that was paying them $15,000 a year.

185
00:15:37,500 --> 00:15:41,500
 But now they've got to take a cut and they're going to make $12,000 a year.

186
00:15:41,500 --> 00:15:46,500
 And so the credit card company comes to them and says, we want you to increase your payments.

187
00:15:46,500 --> 00:15:50,500
 How are they going to increase their payments?

188
00:15:50,500 --> 00:15:52,500
 They're making less money.

189
00:15:52,500 --> 00:15:53,500
 Ditto for Europe.

190
00:15:53,500 --> 00:15:54,500
 That's Europe.

191
00:15:54,500 --> 00:16:01,500
 Europe has got a maxed-out credit card and is having to work at cheaper rates.

192
00:16:01,500 --> 00:16:06,500
 The economies cannot sustain 5% growth.

193
00:16:06,500 --> 00:16:09,500
 Hell, they can't even sustain 2% growth.

194
00:16:09,500 --> 00:16:15,500
 In fact, in some nations, it will be even a question of whether they can continue any contribution to NATO.

195
00:16:15,500 --> 00:16:24,500
 So what we're witnessing really is the collapse, the start of the collapse of NATO.

196
00:16:24,500 --> 00:16:26,500
 NATO exists on paper.

197
00:16:26,500 --> 00:16:27,500
 It's not.

198
00:16:27,500 --> 00:16:29,500
 It's now more of a theoretical concept.

199
00:16:29,500 --> 00:16:33,500
 But in terms of being a viable military force, it's not.

200
00:16:34,500 --> 00:16:38,500
 So is Europe already a victim of its own policies?

201
00:16:38,500 --> 00:16:40,500
 Yes, very much so.

202
00:16:40,500 --> 00:16:42,500
 This is a self-inflicted wound.

203
00:16:42,500 --> 00:16:47,500
 They've gone along entirely with what the United States wanted.

204
00:16:47,500 --> 00:16:57,500
 is allowing to impose sanctions on Russia and to try to cut off the flow of cheap oil and natural gas from Russia.

205
00:16:57,500 --> 00:16:59,500
 It doesn't hurt Russia.

206
00:16:59,500 --> 00:17:00,500
 Russia.

207
00:17:00,500 --> 00:17:01,500
 Russia's got other markets.

208
00:17:01,500 --> 00:17:12,500
 You know, the Europeans need to look at a map and say, you know, there are like 1.5 billion Indians.

209
00:17:12,500 --> 00:17:15,500
 And there's 1.3 billion Chinese.

210
00:17:15,500 --> 00:17:20,500
 There are maybe only 300 million of us total.

211
00:17:20,500 --> 00:17:22,500
 Hmm.

212
00:17:22,500 --> 00:17:28,500
 Where's, you know, Russia can get rid of Europe as a market.

213
00:17:28,500 --> 00:17:29,500
 It has effectively.

214
00:17:29,500 --> 00:17:32,500
 And it's moved into India and China.

215
00:17:32,500 --> 00:17:36,500
 And it will move into other countries in the global south.

216
00:17:36,500 --> 00:17:39,500
 So this was a self-inflicted wound.

217
00:17:39,500 --> 00:17:43,500
 You know, they just, the Europeans did not have the leverage, the control.

218
00:17:43,500 --> 00:17:47,500
 But Europeans fear the outbreak of war.

219
00:17:47,500 --> 00:17:50,500
 Some countries are preparing their citizens.

220
00:17:50,500 --> 00:17:55,500
 Should Europe be worried about the spreading, about the conflict spreading?

221
00:17:55,500 --> 00:18:00,500
 It's not going to spread because Russia attacks them.

222
00:18:00,500 --> 00:18:06,500
 It will only spread if they continue to provide weapons that are used to attack Russia.

223
00:18:07,500 --> 00:18:18,500
 You know, if you had a neighbor across the street from you that had a gun, but didn't own any of the ammunition.

224
00:18:18,500 --> 00:18:24,500
 And a neighbor up the street was the one continuing bringing ammunition to fire at your house.

225
00:18:24,500 --> 00:18:27,500
 Would you be mad just at the guy firing at you?

226
00:18:27,500 --> 00:18:29,500
 Or also at the neighbor up the street?

227
00:18:29,500 --> 00:18:31,500
 You'd be upset with the neighbor up the street.

228
00:18:31,500 --> 00:18:33,500
 That's what Europe is.

229
00:18:33,500 --> 00:18:36,500
 Europe is a facilitator of violence.

230
00:18:36,500 --> 00:18:39,500
 And Russia recognizes it.

231
00:18:39,500 --> 00:18:44,500
 Russia is in a position that it could crush Europe if it wanted to.

232
00:18:45,500 --> 00:18:48,500
 But that's not what the Russians want.

233
00:18:48,500 --> 00:19:01,500
 The one thing the people of Europe need to understand is that Russia comprehends the costs of war far more than most Europeans.

234
00:19:01,500 --> 00:19:07,500
 Now, admittedly, you know, the French and Germans suffered terribly in World War II.

235
00:19:07,500 --> 00:19:11,500
 But not on the scale that the Russians did.

236
00:19:11,500 --> 00:19:18,500
 And that's made even the Russians more reluctant to go to war, to risk spreading war.

237
00:19:18,500 --> 00:19:25,500
 You know, this, if anything, Europe, Europe should be a natural ally with Russia.

238
00:19:25,500 --> 00:19:29,500
 But instead, they've chosen to be hostile.

239
00:19:29,500 --> 00:19:33,500
 So, are dark times ahead?

240
00:19:33,500 --> 00:19:35,500
 Yes.

241
00:19:35,500 --> 00:19:38,500
 Yes, I do believe so, particularly for Europe.

242
00:19:38,500 --> 00:19:45,500
 Europe does not, Europe is not blessed with a quantity of natural resources.

243
00:19:46,500 --> 00:19:49,500
 It has basically de-industrialized.

244
00:19:49,500 --> 00:19:53,500
 It has surrendered in large measure to the green agenda.

245
00:19:53,500 --> 00:19:57,500
 And in the green agenda, given up nuclear power plants.

246
00:19:57,500 --> 00:20:02,500
 And, you know, opted for solar energy.

247
00:20:02,500 --> 00:20:05,500
 Good in theory, but it is terrible in practice.

248
00:20:05,500 --> 00:20:06,500
 Doesn't really work.

249
00:20:06,500 --> 00:20:12,500
 And then has opted for this hostility towards Russia.

250
00:20:13,500 --> 00:20:17,500
 And, you know, Russia is not looking for a fight.

251
00:20:17,500 --> 00:20:21,500
 But if you provoke them, they will strike back.

252
00:20:21,500 --> 00:20:25,500
 And they have the potential to do enormous damage to Europe.

253
00:20:25,500 --> 00:20:32,500
 So, it's, there's no good, there is no good news on the horizon economically or militarily.

254
00:20:33,500 --> 00:20:35,500
 Yeah, Europe is in an economic crisis.

255
00:20:35,500 --> 00:20:39,500
 The reason for which is the halt in Russian gas supplies.

256
00:20:39,500 --> 00:20:41,500
 We had sabotage of Nord Stream.

257
00:20:41,500 --> 00:20:44,500
 The sabotage has already happened.

258
00:20:44,500 --> 00:20:47,500
 And now the pipeline through Ukraine has also been cut off.

259
00:20:47,500 --> 00:20:52,500
 You spoke at the United Nations Security Council about this sabotage.

260
00:20:53,500 --> 00:20:55,500
 What do we know about it so far?

261
00:20:55,500 --> 00:21:01,500
 Well, I think Seymour Hersh, who I, you know, full disclosure, is a good friend of mine.

262
00:21:01,500 --> 00:21:06,500
 Well, I've known him now for, oh Lord, 40, almost 45 years.

263
00:21:06,500 --> 00:21:10,500
 So, he is a genuinely old friend.

264
00:21:11,500 --> 00:21:12,500
 He got the story right.

265
00:21:12,500 --> 00:21:17,500
 It was a CIA, it was a CIA operation carried out at the direction of the Biden White House.

266
00:21:17,500 --> 00:21:20,500
 And it was, it was done for one purpose.

267
00:21:20,500 --> 00:21:24,500
 Force the Europeans to buy U.S. natural gas.

268
00:21:24,500 --> 00:21:27,500
 Make the United States wealthy again.

269
00:21:27,500 --> 00:21:31,500
 It didn't matter if Europe got impoverished in the process.

270
00:21:32,500 --> 00:21:39,500
 It was, while it was a blow to Russia, it was not a devastating blow because Russia had alternatives in other markets.

271
00:21:39,500 --> 00:21:50,500
 We have seen, since then, the actions of Vladimir Zelensky and closing off in the oil shipments that were coming through Ukraine.

272
00:21:50,500 --> 00:21:53,500
 Through the existing pipeline.

273
00:21:53,500 --> 00:21:57,500
 And in cutting that off, again, it hurts Europe.

274
00:21:57,500 --> 00:21:59,500
 It even hurts Ukraine.

275
00:22:00,500 --> 00:22:04,500
 Ukraine was getting upwards of a billion dollars a year just for letting the gas flow.

276
00:22:04,500 --> 00:22:13,500
 And then just two days ago, three days ago, Ukraine launched an attempted attack on the TurkStream pipeline.

277
00:22:13,500 --> 00:22:15,500
 That's right.

278
00:22:15,500 --> 00:22:20,500
 So, Zelensky is acting at the behest of the United States, I firmly believe.

279
00:22:21,500 --> 00:22:34,500
 And this is, what the United States is trying to do is create complete energy dependence on the part of Russia, on the part of Europe, where they'll ignore Russia and then have to rely strictly upon the United States.

280
00:22:34,500 --> 00:22:40,500
 So, will Europe become a victim of its trust in the U.S.?

281
00:22:41,500 --> 00:22:42,500
 I think it's already a victim of its trust.

282
00:22:42,500 --> 00:22:43,500
 Yes.

283
00:22:43,500 --> 00:22:44,500
 Okay.

284
00:22:44,500 --> 00:22:47,500
 So, it has been, you know, it's been victimized.

285
00:22:47,500 --> 00:23:04,500
 You know, it is, Europe is behaving like an abused spouse, you know, whose partner constantly beats them and abuses them and yells at them.

286
00:23:05,500 --> 00:23:07,500
 And yet, the person doesn't leave.

287
00:23:07,500 --> 00:23:10,500
 They stay in that relationship.

288
00:23:10,500 --> 00:23:12,500
 They take the abuse.

289
00:23:12,500 --> 00:23:29,500
 I mean, really, it's sort of embarrassing to watch Europe behave in such a servile manner, to be nothing more than a toothless poodle attached to a U.S. leash.

290
00:23:30,500 --> 00:23:33,500
 You know, they do what the United States tells them to do.

291
00:23:33,500 --> 00:23:36,500
 So, it means we need a new leader.

292
00:23:36,500 --> 00:23:39,500
 Who could become Europe's new leader?

293
00:23:39,500 --> 00:23:45,500
 I don't think there is anybody now that would pass muster.

294
00:23:45,500 --> 00:23:47,500
 Europe is too deeply divided.

295
00:23:48,500 --> 00:24:07,500
 If you look at, you know, like in France, a conservative like Marie Le Pen, she, you know, she won the plurality of the election, but the other parties, the minority parties conspired and got enough cooperation between them to prevent her from taking office.

296
00:24:08,500 --> 00:24:14,500
 I think you're going to see the same with Alice Weidel in Germany with the AfD.

297
00:24:14,500 --> 00:24:26,500
 The kind of leader who, in theory, should speak, you know, speaks best on behalf of European interests right now, I think, is Viktor Orban in Hungary.

298
00:24:27,500 --> 00:24:36,500
 You know, the rest, the Brits, the French, the Germans, the Dutch, the Danes, Norwegians, everybody rejects him.

299
00:24:36,500 --> 00:24:39,500
 So, there is no consensus.

300
00:24:39,500 --> 00:24:41,500
 That's part of the problem.

301
00:24:41,500 --> 00:24:48,500
 And I think it's only out of chaos that a possible new leadership will emerge.

302
00:24:49,500 --> 00:24:50,500
 Yeah, that's true.

303
00:24:50,500 --> 00:24:52,500
 Let us shift back to the USA.

304
