00:29:09,500 --> 00:29:14,500
 The only way you have to calm them down is you get a tranquilizer dart and shoot them with it.

360
00:29:14,500 --> 00:29:15,500
 You know, put them to sleep.

361
00:29:15,500 --> 00:29:21,500
 Otherwise, they're going to continue to agitate for war, expanding the war.

362
00:29:21,500 --> 00:29:23,500
 They can't help themselves.

363
00:29:24,500 --> 00:29:25,500
 Okay.

364
00:29:25,500 --> 00:29:31,500
 We talked about Israel 25 minutes ago, but what is next for the Middle East?

365
00:29:31,500 --> 00:29:35,500
 Experts warn that Israel could attack Iran.

366
00:29:35,500 --> 00:29:37,500
 How realistic is that?

367
00:29:37,500 --> 00:29:41,500
 I think it's growing less likely with each passing day.

368
00:29:41,500 --> 00:29:47,500
 Three weeks ago, four weeks ago, I thought it was highly likely.

369
00:29:48,500 --> 00:30:05,500
 And it all rested up on Israel's assumption that Iran was weakened, dramatically weakened, had no air defense, and that they could easily attack and destroy their nuclear capability or facilities that are engaged with working on nuclear material.

370
00:30:05,500 --> 00:30:18,500
 Well, two days from now, Russia is going to sign a security arrangement, a comprehensive security, strategic security deal with Iran that will encompass economic, political,

371
00:30:18,500 --> 00:30:21,500
 as well as military cooperation.

372
00:30:21,500 --> 00:30:43,500
 I don't know if they'll necessarily qualify it as a mutual defense pact, but what it does mean is that they're putting down on paper Russia's commitment to help defend Iran and help Iran recover economically from what they view as illegal international sanctions, economic sanctions.

373
00:30:45,500 --> 00:30:58,500
 The fact that Russia and China have been regularly conducting military exercises with Iran over the last five years is another consideration someone like Israel has to take into account.

374
00:30:58,500 --> 00:31:06,500
 If they're attacking Iran, are they also running the risk of widening the war to having to fight Russia and China?

375
00:31:06,500 --> 00:31:27,500
 So I see with the entrance of Donald Trump, while there's clearly members in his administration or proposed nominees for the administration, that they'll be agitating to do something militarily about Iran.

376
00:31:27,500 --> 00:31:37,500
 But, you know, all of that talk, it's predicated on people who have never actually had to carry out those kinds of military operations.

377
00:31:37,500 --> 00:31:46,500
 It is, you know, all we have to do is look back at the bombings that the United States did in Iraq.

378
00:31:46,500 --> 00:31:47,500
 And 2003.

379
00:31:47,500 --> 00:31:52,500
 We had complete control of the air.

380
00:31:52,500 --> 00:31:56,500
 There was no air defense system threatening us.

381
00:31:56,500 --> 00:32:02,500
 We could fly wherever we wanted, drop whatever we wanted, linger and whatever, however long we wanted.

382
00:32:03,500 --> 00:32:10,500
 Even with that, all of those advantages, we did not defeat Iraq on the ground.

383
00:32:10,500 --> 00:32:16,500
 We had to put troops and tanks and armored personnel carriers to move forward.

384
00:32:16,500 --> 00:32:22,500
 All of our bombing didn't destroy all of the capabilities of Iraq.

385
00:32:22,500 --> 00:32:45,500
 So it is simply ludicrous and idiotic to think that either the United States or Israel or both combined could launch any attack on Iran, which would devastate Iran to the point that it could not retaliate and could not inflict greater damage on both the United States and Israel.

386
00:32:45,500 --> 00:32:46,500
 Okay.

387
00:32:46,500 --> 00:32:55,500
 And my final question, you hope Trump will make America great again and the rest of the world and Europe, what, poor?

388
00:32:55,500 --> 00:33:14,500
 No, listen, if making America great again means, in my mind, America staying home, minding its own damn business and learning to be friends with others, you know, learning to help promote their interests, not figure out.

389
00:33:14,500 --> 00:33:18,500
 How can we screw them out of something that we want?

390
00:33:18,500 --> 00:33:20,500
 How can we take advantage of them?

391
00:33:20,500 --> 00:33:22,500
 How can we rob them?

392
00:33:22,500 --> 00:33:27,500
 Because right now, you know, the United States, the United States is a bully.

393
00:33:27,500 --> 00:33:33,500
 We demand that other countries do what we want.

394
00:33:33,500 --> 00:33:39,500
 And yet if those other countries exacted a similar demand on us, we would be outraged.

395
00:33:39,500 --> 00:33:40,500
 Yeah.

396
00:33:40,500 --> 00:33:47,500
 So my idea of America making America great again is let's clean up our own mess at home.

397
00:33:47,500 --> 00:33:58,500
 Let's take of our let's take care of our problems of crummy, deteriorating infrastructure, homelessness, you know, weak industrial output.

398
00:33:58,500 --> 00:34:09,500
 Let's see if we can correct those, you know, fix if you want to go lecture other people about becoming physically fit and leaving a healthy lifestyle.

399
00:34:09,500 --> 00:34:17,500
 You don't want to be the person that's drinking two bottles of Slivovitz and smoking cigars and overweight.

400
00:34:17,500 --> 00:34:18,500
 Okay.

401
00:34:18,500 --> 00:34:19,500
 Okay.

